## ⚠️ MAJOR DISCOVERY: GetModuleRelationships() Already Exists

storage.GetModuleRelationships(db, specID) at queries.go:502 returns ALL maintains/interfaces/implements/adjacent relationships from the module_relationships table. This dramatically simplifies cascade:

**Old approach (BFS through cross_references)**:
Complex reverse traversal using GetBacklinks, resolving source_file_id to module.

**New approach (direct relationship lookup)**:
```go
rels, _ := storage.GetModuleRelationships(db, specID)
// Build invariant → modules map
invToModules := map[string][]AffectedModule{}
for _, r := range rels {
    if r.RelType == "interfaces" || r.RelType == "maintains" {
        // r.Target = invariant ID, find module via r.ModuleID
        invToModules[r.Target] = append(invToModules[r.Target], ...)
    }
}
// For cascade of elementID: look up invToModules[elementID]
affected := invToModules[elementID]
```

The BFS approach is still useful for TRANSITIVE cascade (A interfaces B, B interfaces C → changing A affects C through B). But for direct cascade (depth=1), the module_relationships table gives exact results instantly.

**Recommendation**: Use module_relationships for depth=1 (the common case), fall back to BFS for depth>1.

